# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: onnx
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In machine learning, a **neural network** (**NN**) or **neural net**, is a computational model inspired by the structure and functions of biological neural networks.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A neural network consists of connected units or nodes called *artificial neurons*, which loosely model the neurons in the brain.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neuron models that mimic biological neurons more closely have also been recently investigated and shown to significantly improve performance.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are connected by *edges*, which model the synapses in the brain.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each artificial neuron receives signals from connected neurons, then processes them and sends a signal to other connected neurons.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The "signal" is a real number, and the output of each neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the totality of its inputs, called the *activation function*.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The strength of the signal at each connection is determined by a *weight*, which adjusts as part of the training process.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Groups of neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each layer performs a transformation on its inputs.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the *input layer*) to the last layer (the *output layer*), typically passing through multiple intermediate layers (*hidden layers*).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A network is typically called a deep neural network if it has at least two hidden layers.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are capable of learning sophisticated hierarchical representations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training neural networks is a compute-intensive process, accelerated by the use of graphics processing units (GPUs), and large datasets.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Architectural innovations such as convolutional neural networks (CNNs) significantly improved performance in computer vision tasks, while recurrent neural networks (RNNs) enabled modeling of sequential data such as speech and time-series information.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformer architectures introduced attention mechanisms that allow neural networks to model long-range dependencies in data and have the basis of large language models.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks are used for a myriad of tasks including chatbots, large-scale text, image, and video generation, and robotics.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the instance of a ring textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep neural networks are based on statistics developed over 200 years ago.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest kind of feedforward neural network (FNN) is a linear network, which consists of a single layer of output nodes with linear activation functions; the inputs are fed directly to the outputs via weights.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The sum of the products of the weights and the inputs is calculated at each node.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The mean squared errors between these calculated outputs and the given target values are minimized by adjusting to the weights.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This technique is the method of least squares or linear regression.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used to find a rough linear fit to a set of points by Legendre (1805) and Gauss (1795) for the prediction of planetary movement.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Computers are based on John von Neumann's model.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] They execute explicit lists of instructions with access to memory to record their changing state.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks instead originated from efforts to model information processing in biological systems via connectionism.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unlike the von Neumann model, connectionist computing does not separate memory and processing.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts (1943) considered a non-learning computational model for neural networks.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This model paved the way for research to split into one branch focused on biological processes and another focused on artificial intelligence.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] McCulloch and Pitts also developed mathematical models of artificial neurons capable of representing logical functions.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb proposed a learning hypothesis based on neural plasticity that became known as Hebbian learning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was used in many early neural network experiments, such as Rosenblatt's perceptron and the Hopfield network.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Farley and Clark (1954) used computational machines to simulate a Hebbian network.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Other neural networks computational machines were created by Rochester, Holland, Habit and Duda (1956).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1958, psychologist Frank Rosenblatt described the perceptron, one of the first implemented neural networks, funded by the United States Office of Naval Research.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Joseph (1960) mentioned an earlier perceptron-like device by B.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first perceptrons did not have adaptive hidden units.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, Joseph (1960) discussed multilayer that did.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rosenblatt (1962) cited and adopted these ideas, crediting work by H.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, these early efforts did not lead to a working learning algorithm for hidden units, i.e., deep learning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The perceptron raised public excitement in neural networks, causing the US government to drastically increase funding.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This contributed to "the Golden Age of AI", fueled by the optimistic claims made by computer scientists regarding the ability of perceptrons to emulate human intelligence.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Artificial neural networks were identified as a promising direction for artificial intelligence research in the 1955 proposal for the Dartmouth Summer Research Project on Artificial Intelligence.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural network models initially faced major limitations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hardware constraints limited network size and training efficiency, while theoretical understanding of learning algorithms remained incomplete.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many models used single-layer perceptrons, which were restricted to solving linearly separable problems.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] These limitations were highlighted in the book *Perceptrons* by Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert, which deflated interest during the late 1960s and 1970s.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fundamental research was conducted on NNs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Valentin Lapa in the Soviet Union (1965).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, generalizing Rosenblatt's perceptron.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, training layer by layer via regression analysis.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Superfluous hidden units were pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The activation functions of the nodes were Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron (MLP) trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student S.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tuning made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the dominant technique for reducing loss (error).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1969, Kunihiko Fukushima introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] RelLU is the most common activation function.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nevertheless, research stagnated in the United States after Minsky and Papert (1969), who emphasized that perceptrons were incapable of processing the exclusive-or circuit.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, this insight was irrelevant for the deep networks of Ivakhnenko (1965) and Amari (1967).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1976, transfer learning was introduced.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Interest in neural networks revived during the 1980s because of the novel backpropagation algorithm, which allowed multi-layer neural networks to be trained efficiently by propagating error gradients backward (from output back to input) through network layers.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is an efficient application of the chain rule derived by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz in 1673 to networks of differentiable nodes.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not describe how to implement this.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Kelley developed a precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1970, Seppo Linnainmaa published the modern form of backpropagation in his master's thesis (1970).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Ostrovski et al. republished it in 1971.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not describe the algorithm).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Rumelhart, et al., popularized backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers and weight replication began with the neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's CNN architecture also introduced max pooling, a popular downsampling procedure for CNNs.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] CNNs have become an essential tool for computer vision.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNNs to phoneme recognition.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It used convolutions, weight sharing, and backpropagation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to recognizing individual letters.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1989, Yann LeCun et al. created a CNN called LeNet for recognizing handwritten ZIP codes on mail.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1990, Wei Zhang implemented a CNN on optical computing hardware.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, a CNN was applied to medical image object segmentation and breast cancer detection in mammograms.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al. that classifies hand-written digits, was applied by banks to recognize numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] From 1988 onward, the use of neural networks transformed the field of protein structure prediction, in particular when the first cascading networks were trained on *profiles* (matrices) produced by multiple sequence alignments.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] One source of RNN was statistical mechanics.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari proposed to modify the weights of an Ising model by Hebbian learning rule as a model of associative memory, adding in learning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was popularized as the Hopfield network by John Hopfield (1982).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The word "recurrent" is used to describe loop-like structures in anatomy.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1901, Cajal observed "recurrent semicircles" in the cerebellar cortex.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hebb considered "reverberating circuit" as an explanation for short-term memory.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The McCulloch and Pitts paper (1943) considered neural networks that contain cycles, and noted that the current activity of such networks can be affected by activity indefinitely far in the past.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1982 Crossbar Adaptive Array, a recurrent neural network with an array architecture (rather than a multilayer perceptron architecture), used direct recurrent connections from the output to the supervisor (teaching) inputs.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In addition to computing actions (decisions), it computed internal state evaluations (emotions) of consequence situations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Eliminating the external supervisor, it introduced the self-learning method in neural networks.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In cognitive psychology, the *American Psychologist* journal in the early 1980s debated the relation between cognition and emotion.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Social psychologist Robert Zajonc in 1980 stated that emotion is computed first and is independent from cognition, while Richard Lazarus in 1982 stated that cognition is computed first and is inseparable from emotion.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It was an example of a debate where an RNN contributed to an issue and also addressed cognitive psychology.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990) applied RNN to study cognitive psychology.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep RNNs.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed the "neural sequence chunker" or "neural history compressor" which introduced self-supervised pre-training (the "P" in ChatGPT) and neural knowledge distillation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor system solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 1991, Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem and proposed recurrent residual connections to solve it.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] He and Schmidhuber introduced long short-term memory (LSTM), which set accuracy records in multiple application domains.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This was not the ultimate version of LSTM, which required the forget gate, and was introduced in 1999.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It became the default choice for RNN architecture.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, and others, including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] These were designed for unsupervised learning of deep generative models.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Between 2009 and 2012, NNs began winning prizes in image recognition contests, approaching human performance on various tasks, initially in pattern recognition and handwriting recognition.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2011, *DanNet,* a CNN by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further incremental improvements included the VGG-16 network by Karen Simonyan and Andrew Zisserman and Google's Inceptionv3.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2012, Ng and Dean created a network that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, from training only on unlabeled images.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised pre-training and increased computing power from GPUs and distributed computing allowed the use of larger networks, particularly in image and visual recognition problems, which became known as "deep learning".
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Radial basis function and wavelet networks were introduced in 2013.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] These can be shown to offer best approximation properties and have been applied in nonlinear system identification and classification applications.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Generative adversarial networks (GANs) (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) became state of the art in generative modeling from 2014–2018.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] GAN was originally published in 1991 by Schmidhuber, who called it "artificial curiosity": two neural networks contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The first network is a generative model that models a probability distribution over output patterns.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The second network learns by gradient descent to predict the reactions of the environment to these patterns.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Excellent image quality was achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Here, the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Image generation by GAN reached popular success, and provoked discussions concerning deepfakes.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling thereafter, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "[a] very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stacking too many layers led to a steep reduction in training accuracy, known as the "degradation" problem.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In 2015, training very deep networks advanced with the highway network, published in May, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in December.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] ResNet behaves like an open-gated Highway Net.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] During the 2010s, the seq2seq model was developed, and attention mechanisms were added.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This led to the modern transformer architecture in 2017 in "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It requires computation time that is quadratic in the size of the context window.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Schmidhuber's fast weight controller (1992) scales linearly and was later shown to be equivalent to the unnormalized linear transformer.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers have increasingly become the model of choice for natural language processing.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Many modern large language models such as GPT, Gemini, Grok, DeepSeek, and Qwen use this architecture.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs began as an attempt to replicate the architecture of the brain in the digital realm.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs immediately showed promise for handling non-linear relationships, but encountered obstacles.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models soon reoriented to applying mathematical insights to improve empirical results, at the expense of biological fidelity.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are composed of digital neurons, conceptually derived from biological neurons.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron has one or more numerical inputs and produces a single numerical output.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] An input (e.g., an image) is typically parceled across the set of input neurons (each getting a piece of the image).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Each neuron's inputs, weighted by the weights of the connections from each of those inputs are summed.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A bias term is added to this sum.) The result is then passed through a nonlinear activation function to produce the neuron's output.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Small enough outputs may be zeroed out (ignored).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs connect neurons to each other, using the output of some neurons as the input of others, akin to biological axon-synapse-dendrite connections.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The network forms a directed, weighted graph.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weights apply to both the graph's the nodes and edges.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Nodes are arranged in layers, with the bottom layers directly addressing raw data, while the top layers reveal the final results.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Intermediate layers gradually increase the level of abstraction, so what began as for example, pixels in an image, gradually resolves into things such as object boundaries, and then into real-world objects such as letters and faces.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Single layer and unlayered networks are also used.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Multiple connection patterns have been used.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Traditionally, they are *fully connected*, with every neuron in one layer connecting to every neuron in the next layer.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, in convolutional neural networks, some layers are *convolutional,* meaning each neuron in one layer is connected to a subset of neurons in the previous layer, such as those representing one section of an image.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In most neural networks, the outputs of the neurons in one layer are connected only to neurons in the immediately following layer (directed acyclic graph), meaning information only flows forward from one layer to the next.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] These are known as feedforward networks.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In contrast, networks that allow connections between neurons in the same or previous layers are known as recurrent networks.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training/learning involves adjusting the weights of the network to improve the accuracy of the result.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs typically require vast numbers of sample inputs (far more than biological brains) to achieve a given level of function.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is done by minimizing the observed errors among sample observations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training takes place before a network is deployed, and (unlike brains) does not continue thereafter.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network may be retrained from scratch as more sample data becomes available.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Empirical risk minimization adjusts node and link weights to minimize the difference (empirical risk), between the predicted output and the known values in the training samples.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A defined loss function measures the degree of error.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation spreads the error (adjusts the weights) from the output nodes across the network to the input nodes.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The intent is to allow the network to process data that is not included in the training samples.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] As long as the value of the loss function (its cost) continues to decline, the network is continuing to improve.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The function typically produces a statistic whose value is only approximate.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the cost is low, the difference between the output (*e.g.* almost certainly a cat) and the correct answer (a cat) is small.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Most learning models can be viewed as a straightforward application of optimization theory and statistical estimation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning typically ends when additional observations do not usefully reduce the cost.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost typically approaches, but does not reach, 0.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] If no feasible amount of sample data yields a low cost, training is labeled a failure.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] While it is possible to assess a loss function ad hoc, typically it must exhibit desirable properties such as convexity, differentiability, and robustness.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a probabilistic model, the model's posterior probability can be used as an inverse cost (higher values are better).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Backpropagation is a method used to adjust the connection weights to compensate for errors found during learning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The error amount is essentially divided among the connections.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Technically, backpropagation calculates the gradient (the derivative) of the loss function associated with a given state with respect to the weights.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The weight updates can be done via stochastic gradient descent or other methods, such as *extreme learning machines*, "no-prop" networks, training without backtracking, "weightless" networks, and non-connectionist neural networks.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A hyperparameter is a parameter defining any configurable part of the network and learning process whose value is set prior to training.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Examples of hyperparameters include learning rate, sample batch size, number of nodes and layers, etc .
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The performance of a neural network is strongly influenced by hyperparameter choices, and thus may be adjusted during training (typically between training runs), a process called hyperparameter tuning or hyperparameter optimization.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning rate defines the size of the corrective steps that the model takes to adjust for errors in each observation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A high learning rate shortens training time, but with lower ultimate accuracy, while a lower learning rate takes longer, but with the potential for greater accuracy.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Optimizations such as quickprop are primarily aimed at accelerating learning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In order to avoid oscillations such as connection weights that cycle between high and low values, and to improve the rate of convergence, refinements use an adaptive learning rate that increases or decreases as appropriate.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The concept of momentum allows the balance between the gradient and the previous change to be weighted such that the weight adjustment depends to some degree on the previous change.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A momentum close to 0 emphasizes the gradient, while a value close to 1 emphasizes the last change.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Machine learning has involved a variety of approaches to training models, including supervised learning, unsupervised learning, reinforcement learning, and self-supervised learning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning pairs inputs and desired outputs.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The learning task is to produce the desired output for each input.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In this case, the cost is related to eliminating incorrect outputs.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A commonly used cost is the mean-squared error, which tries to minimize the average squared error between the network's output and the desired output.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Tasks suited for supervised learning include pattern recognition (classification) and regression (function approximation).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised learning is applicable to sequential data (e.g., for handwriting, speech and gesture recognition).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This can be thought of as learning with a "teacher", in the form of a function that provides continuous feedback.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In unsupervised learning, input data is given along with the cost function for the data $\textstyle x$ and the output, without an "answer sheet".
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function is dependent on the task (the model domain) and reflects *a priori* assumptions (implicit model properties, its parameters and the observed variables).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, the model $\textstyle f(x)=a$ treats $\textstyle a$ is a constant and the cost $\textstyle C=E[(x-f(x))^{2}]$ .
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Minimizing this cost produces a value of $\textstyle a$ that is equal to the mean of the data.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The cost function can be much more complicated.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its form depends on the application: for example, in compression it could be related to the mutual information between $\textstyle x$ and $\textstyle f(x)$ , whereas in statistical modeling, it could be related to the posterior probability (in both examples, those quantities are maximized).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Unsupervised learning is typically applied to estimation problems; applications include clustering, the estimation of statistical distributions, compression, and filtering.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning (SSL) is a paradigm in machine learning where a model is trained on a task using the data itself to generate supervisory signals, rather than relying on externally-provided labels.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In the context of neural networks, self-supervised learning aims to leverage inherent structures or relationships within the input data to create meaningful training signals.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] SSL tasks are designed so that solving them requires capturing essential features or relationships in the data.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The input data is typically augmented or transformed in a way that creates pairs of related samples, where one sample serves as the input, and the other is used to formulate the supervisory signal.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This augmentation can involve introducing noise, cropping, rotation, or other transformations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning more closely imitates the way humans learn to classify objects.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In applications such as playing video games, an actor takes a string of actions, receiving a generally unpredictable response from the environment (the game) after each one.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The goal is to win the game (get the highest score).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In reinforcement learning, the aim is to weight the network to increase the score.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] After each action the game generates an observation and an instantaneous cost, according to its rules.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The rules and the long-term cost can only be estimated.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] At any juncture, the agent decides whether to explore new actions to uncover their costs or to exploit prior learning to proceed more quickly.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Formally, the environment is modeled as a Markov decision process (MDP) with states $\textstyle {s_{1},...,s_{n}}\in S$ and actions $\textstyle {a_{1},...,a_{m}}\in A$ .
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Taken together, the two define a Markov chain (MC).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The aim is to discover the lowest-cost MC.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Self-learning was introduced in 1982 along with a *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA) NN that could teach itself.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation s, and only one output, action (or behavior) a.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It has neither external advice input nor external reinforcement from the environment.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about encountered situations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, its behavioral environment, and its genetic environment, from which it receives initial emotions (only once) about to be encountered situations in the behavioral environment.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Having received the genome vector (species vector) from the genetic environment, the CAA will learn a goal-seeking behavior, in the behavioral environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution can create NN topologies and weights using evolutionary computation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is competitive with gradient descent approaches.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neuroevolution may be less prone to get caught in "dead ends".
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Topological deep learning, introduced in 2017, integrates topology with deep neural networks to address high-order data.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Initially rooted in algebraic topology, TDL evolved into a versatile framework incorporating tools from mathematical disciplines such as differential topology and geometric topology.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In a Bayesian framework, a distribution over the set of allowed models is chosen to minimize cost.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Evolutionary methods, gene expression programming, simulated annealing, expectation–maximization, non-parametric methods and particle swarm optimization are other learning algorithms.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Convergent recursion is a learning algorithm for cerebellar model articulation controller (CMAC) neural networks.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Learning can be either stochastic or batch.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning creates a weight adjustment for each sample.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In batch learning, weights are adjusted based on a batch of inputs, accumulating errors over the batch.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Stochastic learning introduces "noise" into the process, using the local gradient calculated from one data point; this reduces the chance of the network getting stuck in local minima.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, batch learning typically yields a faster, more stable descent to a local minimum, since each update is performed in the direction of the batch's average error.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A common compromise is to use "mini-batches", small batches with samples in each batch selected stochastically from the entire data set.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Types of neural networks (NN) include a family of techniques.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The simplest types have static components, including number of units, number of layers, unit weights and topology.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types allow/require learning to be "supervised" by the operator, while others operate independently.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Some types operate purely in hardware, while others are purely software and run on general purpose computers.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The choice of model depends on the data and the application.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models that work well with textual data are typically not the best choice for image data, etc.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] An important element is which training/learning the model uses.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural architecture search (NAS) uses machine learning to automate NN design.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NAS has yielded networks that compare well with hand-designed systems.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The basic algorithm is to propose a candidate model, evaluate it against a dataset, and use the results as feedback to teach the NAS network.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Efforts include AutoML and AutoKeras. scikit-learn library provides functions to help with building a deep network from scratch.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are design choices (they are not learned).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The multilayer perceptron is a universal function approximator, as proven by the universal approximation theorem.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] However, the proof does not specify the number of neurons required, the network topology, the weights or the learning parameters.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A recurrent architecture with rational-valued weights (as opposed to full precision real number-valued weights) has the power of a universal Turing machine, using a finite number of neurons and linear connections.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Further, the use of irrational values for weights results in a machine with super-Turing power.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A model's "capacity" property is its ability to model any given function.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It is related to the amount of information that can be stored in the network and to the notion of complexity.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Information capacity and the VC dimension are two metrics.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The capacity of a network of standard neurons (not convolutional) can be derived by four rules that derive from considering a neuron as an electrical element.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The information capacity captures the functions that the network can model given any data as input.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC dimension uses the principles of measure theory and finds the maximum capacity under optimal circumstances, given input data in a specific form.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary inputs is half the information capacity of a perceptron.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The VC Dimension for arbitrary points is sometimes referred to as Memory Capacity.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Models may not consistently converge on a single solution, because the system may get stuck in a local minima.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, the optimization method used might not guarantee to converge should it begin far from any local minima.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Thirdly, for sufficiently large data or parameters, some methods are impractically slow/expensive.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Training may also cross some saddle point that may then prevent access to the solution.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] When the width of a network approaches infinity, it is well described by its first order Taylor expansion throughout training, and so inherits the convergence behavior of affine models.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] When parameter numbers are small, NNs often fit target functions from low to high frequencies.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This behavior is referred to as spectral bias, or the frequency principle.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This phenomenon is the opposite of the behavior of some well-studied iterative numerical schemes such as the Jacobi method.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Deeper neural networks are more biased towards low frequency functions.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Applications that must generalize well to unseen examples, must avoid over-training.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This arises in convoluted or over-specified systems when the network capacity is much larger than needed.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Cross-validation and similar techniques can check for over-training and select appropriate hyperparameters to minimize generalization error.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Supervised neural networks that use a mean squared error (MSE) cost function can use formal statistical methods to determine the confidence of the trained model.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] The MSE on a validation set can be used as an estimate for variance.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This value can then be used to calculate the confidence interval of network output, assuming a normal distribution.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] A confidence analysis made this way is statistically valid as long as the output probability distribution stays the same and the network is not modified.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] By adopting a softmax activation function, a generalization of the logistic function, on the output layer of the neural network (or a softmax component in a component-based network) for categorical target variables, the outputs can be interpreted as posterior probabilities.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This is useful in classification as it gives a certainty measure.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks support a broad range of applications in image processing, speech recognition, natural language processing, finance, and medicine.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Because of their ability to model and reproduce nonlinear processes, neural networks have found applications in many disciplines.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to diagnose cancers and to distinguish highly invasive cancer cell lines from less invasive lines using only cell shape data.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to accelerate reliability analysis of infrastructures subject to natural disasters and to predict settling in building foundations.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] They are used to mitigate flooding by modelling rainfall-runoff.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used for building black-box models in geoscience: hydrology, ocean modelling and coastal engineering, and geomorphology.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been employed in cybersecurity, with the objective to discriminate between legitimate and malicious activities.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] For example, machine learning has been used for classifying Android malware, for identifying domains belonging to threat actors and for detecting URLs posing a security risk.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Research is underway on penetration testing, for detecting botnets, credit cards frauds, and network intrusions.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been proposed as a tool to solve partial differential equations in physics and simulate the properties of many-body open quantum systems.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In brain research NNs have studied short-term behavior of individual neurons, the dynamics of neural circuitry arise from interactions between individual neurons and how behavior can arise from abstract neural modules that represent complete subsystems.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Studies considered long-and short-term plasticity of neural systems and their relation to learning and memory from the individual neuron to the system level.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs show promise in profiling a user's interests from photos and discovering new stable materials by efficiently predicting the total energy of crystals.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are employed in computer vision tasks such as image classification, object and facial recognition, and image segmentation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] They have been applied to automated surveillance medical imaging for diagnosis.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used for speaker identification, speech-to-text, and text-to-speech conversion.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have conquered large vocabulary continuous speech recognition, outperforming traditional techniques.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] These advancements have enabled the development of more accurate and efficient voice-activated systems, enhancing user interfaces in technology products.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In natural language processing, NNs are used for tasks such as text classification, sentiment analysis, machine translation, to answer free-form questions, act as chatbots, and to summarize and analyze texts.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] This has implications for automated customer service, content moderation, and language understanding technologies.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs are used to model dynamic systems for tasks such as system identification, control design, autonomous vehicles, and optimization.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Large financial institutions use AI to assist with their investment practices.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] BlackRock's AI engine, Aladdin, is used both within the company and by clients to help with investment decisions.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Its functions include the use of natural language processing to analyze text such as news, broker reports, and social media feeds.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] It then gauges the sentiment on the companies mentioned and assigns a score.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Banks such as UBS and Deutsche Bank use SQREEM (Sequential Quantum Reduction and Extraction Model) to mine data to develop consumer profiles and match them with wealth management products.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] They enhance diagnostic accuracy, especially by interpreting complex medical imaging for early disease detection, and by predicting patient outcomes for personalized treatment planning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] In drug discovery, NNs speed up the identification of potential drug candidates and predict their efficacy and safety, significantly reducing development time and costs.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Additionally, their application in personalized medicine and healthcare data analysis allows tailored therapies and efficient patient care management.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Neural networks are widely applied in cybersecurity for anomaly detection, malware classification, and intrusion detection.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] By learning patterns of normal system or network behavior, NNs can identify deviations that indicate malicious activity.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Transformers are used for content creation across numerous industries.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] They can analyze samples and produce outputs that match the style of an artist or musician.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] For instance, DALL-E trained on 650 million pairs of images and texts and can create artworks based on user text.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Companies such as AIVA and Jukedeck have used transformers to create original music.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have been used to create personalized advertisements.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] Film production companies have used NNs to analyze the financial success of a film.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p01] NNs have found uses in video game creation.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs require millions of training samples to become functional.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] As of 2026, training a commercial LLM (GPT, Grok, Gemini) typically required hundreds of thousands of computers, and cost 10s of millions of dollars.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] A central claim of NNs is that they embody new and powerful general principles for processing information.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] However, at root they use statistical long-developed methods.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks require enormous computing resources for training.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] While the brain requires only 20 watts of power, training commercial transformers requires (2026) data centers with hundreds of megawatts.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] From 1991 to 2015, computing power, especially as delivered by GPGPUs (on GPUs), increased around a million-fold, enabling the use of the backpropagation algorithm.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neuromorphic engineering or a physical neural network constructed non-von-Neumann chips to directly implement neural networks in circuitry.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, Alphabet introduced custom chips (Tensor Processing Unit).
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] The statistical properties of input data may change over time, a phenomenon known as concept drift or non-stationarity.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Drift can reduce predictive accuracy and lead to unreliable or biased decisions if it is not detected and corrected.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] In practice, this means that the model's accuracy in deployment may differ substantially from levels observed during training.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Neural networks are dependent on the quality of their training data; low quality data can lead the model to product poor results.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Biased data produces biased results, requiring trainers to detect and correct them.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] For example, data that underrepresents some demographic groups may prevent cause errors, e.g., in facial recognition and law enforcement.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] In 2018, Amazon scrapped a recruiting tool because the model favored men over women for jobs in software engineering due to the larger number of male workers in the field.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] The system penalized resumes with the word "woman" or the name of a women's college.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] One corrective is to add synthetic data to offset the bias.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are "black box" systems that have complicated understanding of their decision-making processes.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] NNs are further vulnerable to adversarial examples ("poison"), that can cause incorrect predictions.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] These concerns have led to increased research in explainable artificial intelligence (XAI), robust machine learning, and hybrid AI approaches that combine neural learning with symbolic reasoning.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Advocates of hybrid models also say that such a mixture can better capture the mechanisms of the human mind.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Progress has included local vs. non-local learning and shallow vs. deep architectures.
[src:onnx/artificial-neural-network-p02] Analyzing human thought (a biological neural network) has also proven difficult.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In machine learning, **deep learning** (**DL**) focuses on utilizing multilayered neural networks to perform tasks such as classification, regression, and representation learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The field takes inspiration from biological neuroscience and revolves around stacking artificial neurons into layers and "training" them to process data.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The adjective "deep" refers to the use of multiple layers (ranging from three to several hundred or thousands) in the network.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Methods used can be supervised, semi-supervised or unsupervised.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Some common deep learning network architectures include fully connected networks, deep belief networks, recurrent neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative adversarial networks, transformers, and neural radiance fields.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Early forms of neural networks were inspired by information processing and distributed communication nodes in biological systems, particularly the human brain.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] However, current neural networks do not intend to model the brain function of organisms, and are generally seen as low-quality models for that purpose.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Fundamentally, deep learning refers to a class of machine learning algorithms in which a hierarchy of layers is used to transform input data into a progressively more abstract and composite representation.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] For example, in an image recognition model, the raw input may be an image (represented as a tensor of pixels).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The first representational layer may attempt to identify basic shapes such as lines and circles, the second layer may compose and encode arrangements of edges, the third layer may encode a nose and eyes, and the fourth layer may recognize that the image contains a face.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Importantly, a deep learning process can learn which features to optimally place at which level *on its own*.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Prior to deep learning, machine learning techniques often involved hand-crafted feature engineering to transform the data into a more suitable representation for a classification algorithm to operate on.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In the deep learning approach, features are not hand-crafted and the model discovers useful feature representations from the data automatically.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] This does not eliminate the need for hand-tuning; for example, varying numbers of layers and layer sizes can provide different degrees of abstraction.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The word "deep" in "deep learning" refers to the number of layers through which the data is transformed.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] More precisely, deep learning systems have a substantial *credit assignment path* (CAP) depth.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The CAP is the chain of transformations from input to output.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] CAPs describe potentially causal connections between input and output.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] For a feedforward neural network, the depth of the CAPs is that of the network and is the number of hidden layers plus one (as the output layer is also parameterized).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] For recurrent neural networks, in which a signal may propagate through a layer more than once, the CAP depth is potentially unlimited.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] No universally agreed-upon threshold of depth divides shallow learning from deep learning, but most researchers agree that deep learning involves CAP depth higher than two.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] CAP of depth two has been shown to be a universal approximator in the sense that it can emulate any function.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Beyond that, more layers do not add to the function approximator ability of the network.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep models (CAP > two) are able to extract better features than shallow models and hence, extra layers help in learning the features effectively.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures can be constructed with a greedy layer-by-layer method.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning helps to disentangle these abstractions and pick out which features improve performance.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms can be applied to unsupervised learning tasks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] This is an important benefit because unlabeled data is more abundant than labeled data.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Examples of deep structures that can be trained in an unsupervised manner are deep belief networks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The term *deep learning* was introduced to the machine learning community by Rina Dechter in 1986, and to artificial neural networks by Igor Aizenberg and colleagues in 2000, in the context of Boolean threshold neurons.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The etymology of the term is more complicated.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep neural networks are generally interpreted in terms of the universal approximation theorem or probabilistic inference.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The classic universal approximation theorem concerns the capacity of feedforward neural networks with a single hidden layer of finite size to approximate continuous functions.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 1989, the first proof was published by George Cybenko for sigmoid activation functions and was generalised to feed-forward multi-layer architectures in 1991 by Kurt Hornik.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Recent work also showed that universal approximation also holds for non-bounded activation functions such as Kunihiko Fukushima's rectified linear unit.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The universal approximation theorem for deep neural networks concerns the capacity of networks with bounded width but the depth is allowed to grow.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation derives from the field of machine learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] It features inference, as well as the optimization concepts of training and testing, related to fitting and generalization, respectively.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] More specifically, the probabilistic interpretation considers the activation nonlinearity as a cumulative distribution function.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation led to the introduction of dropout as regularizer in neural networks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The probabilistic interpretation was introduced by researchers including Hopfield, Widrow and Narendra and popularized in surveys such as the one by Bishop.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] There are two types of artificial neural network (ANN): feedforward neural network (FNN) or multilayer perceptron (MLP) and recurrent neural networks (RNN).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] RNNs have cycles in their connectivity structure, whereas FNNs do not.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In the 1920s, Wilhelm Lenz and Ernst Ising created the Ising model which is essentially a non-learning RNN architecture consisting of neuron-like threshold elements.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 1972, Shun'ichi Amari made this architecture adaptive.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] His learning RNN was republished by John Hopfield in 1982.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Other early recurrent neural networks were published by Kaoru Nakano in 1971.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Already in 1948, Alan Turing produced work on "Intelligent Machinery" that was not published in his lifetime, containing "ideas related to artificial evolution and learning RNNs".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Frank Rosenblatt (1958) proposed the perceptron, an MLP with 3 layers: an input layer, a hidden layer with randomized weights that did not learn, and an output layer.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] He later published a 1962 book that also introduced variants and computer experiments, including a version with four-layer perceptrons "with adaptive preterminal networks" where the last two layers have learned weights (here he credits H.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Joseph (1960) "functionally equivalent to a variation of" this four-layer system (the book mentions Joseph over 30 times).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Should Joseph therefore be considered the originator of proper adaptive multilayer perceptrons with learning hidden units?
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Unfortunately, the learning algorithm was not a functional one, and fell into oblivion.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The first working deep learning algorithm was the Group method of data handling, a method to train arbitrarily deep neural networks, published by Alexey Ivakhnenko and Lapa in 1965.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] They regarded it as a form of polynomial regression, or a generalization of Rosenblatt's perceptron to handle more complex, nonlinear, and hierarchical relationships.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] A 1971 paper described a deep network with eight layers trained by this method, which is based on layer by layer training through regression analysis.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Superfluous hidden units are pruned using a separate validation set.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Since the activation functions of the nodes are Kolmogorov-Gabor polynomials, these were also the first deep networks with multiplicative units or "gates".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The first deep learning multilayer perceptron trained by stochastic gradient descent was published in 1967 by Shun'ichi Amari.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In computer experiments conducted by Amari's student Saito, a five layer MLP with two modifiable layers learned internal representations to classify non-linearily separable pattern classes.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Subsequent developments in hardware and hyperparameter tunings have made end-to-end stochastic gradient descent the currently dominant training technique.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The rectifier has become the most popular activation function for deep learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning architectures for convolutional neural networks (CNNs) with convolutional layers and downsampling layers began with the Neocognitron introduced by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1979, though not trained by backpropagation.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The terminology "back-propagating errors" was actually introduced in 1962 by Rosenblatt, but he did not know how to implement this, although Henry J.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Kelley had a continuous precursor of backpropagation in 1960 in the context of control theory.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The modern form of backpropagation was first published in Seppo Linnainmaa's master thesis (1970).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Paul Werbos applied backpropagation to neural networks in 1982 (his 1974 PhD thesis, reprinted in a 1994 book, did not yet describe the algorithm).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Rumelhart et al. popularised backpropagation but did not cite the original work.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel to apply CNN to phoneme recognition.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 1988, Wei Zhang applied a backpropagation-trained CNN to alphabet recognition.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] LeNet-5 (1998), a 7-level CNN by Yann LeCun et al., that classifies digits, was applied by several banks to recognize hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32x32 pixel images.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks (RNN) were further developed in the 1980s.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Recurrence is used for sequence processing, and when a recurrent network is unrolled, it mathematically resembles a deep feedforward layer.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Consequently, they have similar properties and issues, and their developments had mutual influences.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In RNN, two early influential works were the Jordan network (1986) and the Elman network (1990), which applied RNN to study problems in cognitive psychology.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In the 1980s, backpropagation did not work well for deep learning with long credit assignment paths.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] To overcome this problem, in 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber proposed a hierarchy of RNNs pre-trained one level at a time by self-supervised learning where each RNN tries to predict its own next input, which is the next unexpected input of the RNN below.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] This "neural history compressor" uses predictive coding to learn internal representations at multiple self-organizing time scales.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] This can substantially facilitate downstream deep learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The RNN hierarchy can be *collapsed* into a single RNN, by distilling a higher level *chunker* network into a lower level *automatizer* network.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 1993, a neural history compressor solved a "Very Deep Learning" task that required more than 1000 subsequent layers in an RNN unfolded in time.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The "P" in ChatGPT refers to such pre-training.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Sepp Hochreiter's diploma thesis (1991) implemented the neural history compressor, and identified and analyzed the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Hochreiter proposed recurrent residual connections to solve the vanishing gradient problem.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] This led to the long short-term memory (LSTM), published in 1995.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] LSTM can learn "very deep learning" tasks with long credit assignment paths that require memories of events that happened thousands of discrete time steps before.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] That LSTM was not yet the modern architecture, which required a "forget gate", introduced in 1999, which became the standard RNN architecture.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 1991, Jürgen Schmidhuber also published adversarial neural networks that contest with each other in the form of a zero-sum game, where one network's gain is the other network's loss.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, this principle was used in generative adversarial networks (GANs).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] During 1985–1995, inspired by statistical mechanics, several architectures and methods were developed by Terry Sejnowski, Peter Dayan, Geoffrey Hinton, etc., including the Boltzmann machine, restricted Boltzmann machine, Helmholtz machine, and the wake-sleep algorithm.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] However, those were more computationally expensive compared to backpropagation.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Boltzmann machine learning algorithm, published in 1985, was briefly popular before being eclipsed by the backpropagation algorithm in 1986.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] A 1988 network became state of the art in protein structure prediction, an early application of deep learning to bioinformatics.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Both shallow and deep learning (e.g., recurrent nets) of ANNs for speech recognition have been explored for many years.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] These methods never outperformed non-uniform internal-handcrafting Gaussian mixture model/Hidden Markov model (GMM-HMM) technology based on generative models of speech trained discriminatively.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Key difficulties have been analyzed, including gradient diminishing and weak temporal correlation structure in neural predictive models.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Additional difficulties were the lack of training data and limited computing power.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Most speech recognition researchers moved away from neural nets to pursue generative modeling.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] An exception was at SRI International in the late 1990s.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Funded by the US government's NSA and DARPA, SRI researched in speech and speaker recognition.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The speaker recognition team led by Larry Heck reported significant success with deep neural networks in speech processing in the 1998 NIST Speaker Recognition benchmark.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] It was deployed in the Nuance Verifier, representing the first major industrial application of deep learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The raw features of speech, waveforms, later produced excellent larger-scale results.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2003, LSTM became competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, Alex Graves, Santiago Fernández, Faustino Gomez, and Schmidhuber combined it with connectionist temporal classification (CTC) in stacks of LSTMs.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, it became the first RNN to win a pattern recognition contest, in connected handwriting recognition.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2006, publications by Geoff Hinton, Ruslan Salakhutdinov, Osindero and Teh deep belief networks were developed for generative modeling.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] They are trained by training one restricted Boltzmann machine, then freezing it and training another one on top of the first one, and so on, then optionally fine-tuned using supervised backpropagation.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] They could model high-dimensional probability distributions, such as the distribution of MNIST images, but convergence was slow.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The impact of deep learning in industry began in the early 2000s, when CNNs already processed an estimated 10% to 20% of all the checks written in the US, according to Yann LeCun.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Industrial applications of deep learning to large-scale speech recognition started around 2010.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The 2009 NIPS Workshop on Deep Learning for Speech Recognition was motivated by the limitations of deep generative models of speech, and the possibility that given more capable hardware and large-scale data sets that deep neural nets might become practical.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] It was believed that pre-training DNNs using generative models of deep belief nets (DBN) would overcome the main difficulties of neural nets.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The nature of the recognition errors produced by the two types of systems was characteristically different, offering technical insights into how to integrate deep learning into the existing highly efficient, run-time speech decoding system deployed by all major speech recognition systems.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Analysis around 2009–2010, contrasting the GMM (and other generative speech models) vs.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] DNN models, stimulated early industrial investment in deep learning for speech recognition.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] That analysis was done with comparable performance (less than 1.5% in error rate) between discriminative DNNs and generative models.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2010, researchers extended deep learning from TIMIT to large vocabulary speech recognition, by adopting large output layers of the DNN based on context-dependent HMM states constructed by decision trees.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The deep learning revolution started around CNN- and GPU-based computer vision.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Although CNNs trained by backpropagation had been around for decades and GPU implementations of NNs for years, including CNNs, faster implementations of CNNs on GPUs were needed to progress on computer vision.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Later, as deep learning becomes widespread, specialized hardware and algorithm optimizations were developed specifically for deep learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] A key advance for the deep learning revolution was hardware advances, especially GPU.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2009, Raina, Madhavan, and Andrew Ng reported a 100M deep belief network trained on 30 Nvidia GeForce GTX 280 GPUs, an early demonstration of GPU-based deep learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] They reported up to 70 times faster training.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2011, a CNN named *DanNet* by Dan Ciresan, Ueli Meier, Jonathan Masci, Luca Maria Gambardella, and Jürgen Schmidhuber achieved for the first time superhuman performance in a visual pattern recognition contest, outperforming traditional methods by a factor of 3.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] They also showed how max-pooling CNNs on GPU improved performance significantly.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2012, Andrew Ng and Jeff Dean created an FNN that learned to recognize higher-level concepts, such as cats, only from watching unlabeled images taken from YouTube videos.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In October 2012, AlexNet by Alex Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton won the large-scale ImageNet competition by a significant margin over shallow machine learning methods.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The success in image classification was then extended to the more challenging task of generating descriptions (captions) for images, often as a combination of CNNs and LSTMs.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2014, the state of the art was training "very deep neural network" with 20 to 30 layers.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, two techniques were developed to train very deep networks: the highway network was published in May 2015, and the residual neural network (ResNet) in Dec 2015.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Around the same time, deep learning started impacting the field of art.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Early examples included Google DeepDream (2015), and neural style transfer (2015), both of which were based on pretrained image classification neural networks, such as VGG-19.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Generative adversarial network (GAN) by (Ian Goodfellow et al., 2014) (based on Jürgen Schmidhuber's principle of artificial curiosity) became state of the art in generative modeling during 2014-2018 period.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Excellent image quality is achieved by Nvidia's StyleGAN (2018) based on the Progressive GAN by Tero Karras et al.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Here the GAN generator is grown from small to large scale in a pyramidal fashion.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Diffusion models (2015) eclipsed GANs in generative modeling since then, with systems such as DALL·E 2 (2022) and Stable Diffusion (2022).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2015, Google's speech recognition improved by 49% by an LSTM-based model, which they made available through Google Voice Search on smartphone.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning is part of state-of-the-art systems in various disciplines, particularly computer vision and automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Results on commonly used evaluation sets such as TIMIT (ASR) and MNIST (image classification), as well as a range of large-vocabulary speech recognition tasks have steadily improved.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks were superseded for ASR by LSTM. but are more successful in computer vision.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Yoshua Bengio, Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun were awarded the 2018 Turing Award for "conceptual and engineering breakthroughs that have made deep neural networks a critical component of computing".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] An ANN is based on a collection of connected units called artificial neurons, (analogous to biological neurons in a biological brain).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Each connection (synapse) between neurons can transmit a signal to another neuron.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The receiving (postsynaptic) neuron can process the signal(s) and then signal downstream neurons connected to it.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Neurons may have state, generally represented by real numbers, typically between 0 and 1.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Neurons and synapses may also have a weight that varies as learning proceeds, which can increase or decrease the strength of the signal that it sends downstream.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Typically, neurons are organized in layers.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first (input), to the last (output) layer, possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The original goal of the neural network approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Over time, attention focused on matching specific mental abilities, leading to deviations from biology such as backpropagation, or passing information in the reverse direction and adjusting the network to reflect that information.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] As of 2017, neural networks typically have a few thousand to a few million units and millions of connections.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Despite this number being several order of magnitude less than the number of neurons on a human brain, these networks can perform many tasks at a level beyond that of humans (e.g., recognizing faces, or playing "Go").
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] A **deep neural network** (**DNN**) is an artificial neural network with multiple layers between the input and output layers.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] There are different types of neural networks but they always consist of the same components: neurons, synapses, weights, biases, and functions.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] These components as a whole function in a way that mimics functions of the human brain, and can be trained like any other ML algorithm.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] For example, a DNN that is trained to recognize dog breeds will go over the given image and calculate the probability that the dog in the image is a certain breed.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The user can review the results and select which probabilities the network should display (above a certain threshold, etc.) and return the proposed label.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Each mathematical manipulation as such is considered a layer, and complex DNN have many layers, hence the name "deep" networks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] DNNs can model complex non-linear relationships.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] DNN architectures generate compositional models where the object is expressed as a layered composition of primitives.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The extra layers enable composition of features from lower layers, potentially modeling complex data with fewer units than a similarly performing shallow network.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] For instance, it was proved that sparse multivariate polynomials are exponentially easier to approximate with DNNs than with shallow networks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep architectures include many variants of a few basic approaches.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Each architecture has found success in specific domains.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] It is not always possible to compare the performance of multiple architectures, unless they have been evaluated on the same data sets.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are typically feedforward networks in which data flows from the input layer to the output layer without looping back.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] At first, the DNN creates a map of virtual neurons and assigns random numerical values, or "weights", to connections between them.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The weights and inputs are multiplied and return an output between 0 and 1.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] If the network did not accurately recognize a particular pattern, an algorithm would adjust the weights.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] That way the algorithm can make certain parameters more influential, until it determines the correct mathematical manipulation to fully process the data.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Recurrent neural networks, in which data can flow in any direction, are used for applications such as language modeling.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Long short-term memory is particularly effective for this use.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) are used in computer vision.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] CNNs also have been applied to acoustic modeling for automatic speech recognition (ASR).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] As with ANNs, many issues can arise with naively trained DNNs.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Two common issues are overfitting and computation time.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] DNNs are prone to overfitting because of the added layers of abstraction, which allow them to model rare dependencies in the training data.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Regularization methods such as Ivakhnenko's unit pruning or weight decay ( $\ell _{2}$ -regularization) or sparsity ( $\ell _{1}$ -regularization) can be applied during training to combat overfitting.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively dropout regularization randomly omits units from the hidden layers during training.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] This helps to exclude rare dependencies.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Another interesting recent development is research into models of just enough complexity through an estimation of the intrinsic complexity of the task being modelled.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] This approach has been successfully applied for multivariate time series prediction tasks such as traffic prediction.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Finally, data can be augmented via methods such as cropping and rotating such that smaller training sets can be increased in size to reduce the chances of overfitting.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] DNNs must consider many training parameters, such as the size (number of layers and number of units per layer), the learning rate, and initial weights.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Sweeping through the parameter space for optimal parameters may not be feasible due to the cost in time and computational resources.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Various tricks, such as batching (computing the gradient on several training examples at once rather than individual examples) speed up computation.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Large processing capabilities of many-core architectures (such as GPUs or the Intel Xeon Phi) have produced significant speedups in training, because of the suitability of such processing architectures for the matrix and vector computations.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Alternatively, engineers may look for other types of neural networks with more straightforward and convergent training algorithms.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] CMAC (cerebellar model articulation controller) is one such kind of neural network.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] It doesn't require learning rates or randomized initial weights.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The training process can be guaranteed to converge in one step with a new batch of data, and the computational complexity of the training algorithm is linear with respect to the number of neurons involved.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks that contain many layers of non-linear hidden units and a very large output layer.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method for training large-scale commercial cloud AI .
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] OpenAI estimated the hardware computation used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017) and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of computation required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Special electronic circuits called deep learning processors were designed to speed up deep learning algorithms.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Deep learning processors include neural processing units (NPUs) in Huawei cellphones and cloud computing servers such as tensor processing units (TPU) in the Google Cloud Platform.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Cerebras Systems has also built a dedicated system to handle large deep learning models, the CS-2, based on the largest processor in the industry, the second-generation Wafer Scale Engine (WSE-2).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Atomically thin semiconductors are considered promising for energy-efficient deep learning hardware where the same basic device structure is used for both logic operations and data storage.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] In 2020, Marega et al. published experiments with a large-area active channel material for developing logic-in-memory devices and circuits based on floating-gate field-effect transistors (FGFETs).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Feldmann et al. proposed an integrated photonic hardware accelerator for parallel convolutional processing.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] The authors identify two key advantages of integrated photonics over its electronic counterparts: (1) massively parallel data transfer through wavelength division multiplexing in conjunction with frequency combs, and (2) extremely high data modulation speeds.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p01] Their system can execute trillions of multiply-accumulate operations per second, indicating the potential of integrated photonics in data-heavy AI applications.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Large-scale automatic speech recognition is the first and most convincing successful case of deep learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] LSTM RNNs can learn "Very Deep Learning" tasks that involve multi-second intervals containing speech events separated by thousands of discrete time steps, where one time step corresponds to about 10 ms.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] LSTM with forget gates is competitive with traditional speech recognizers on certain tasks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The initial success in speech recognition was based on small-scale recognition tasks based on TIMIT.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The data set contains 630 speakers from eight major dialects of American English, where each speaker reads 10 sentences.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Its small size lets many configurations be tried.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] More importantly, the TIMIT task concerns phone-sequence recognition, which, unlike word-sequence recognition, allows weak phone bigram language models.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This lets the strength of the acoustic modeling aspects of speech recognition be more easily analyzed.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The error rates listed below, including these early results and measured as percent phone error rates (PER), have been summarized since 1991.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] More recent speech recognition models use Transformers or Temporal Convolution Networks with significant success and widespread applications.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] All major commercial speech recognition systems (e.g., Microsoft Cortana, Xbox, Skype Translator, Amazon Alexa, Google Now, Apple Siri, Baidu and iFlyTek voice search, and a range of Nuance speech products, etc.) are based on deep learning.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] A common evaluation set for image classification is the MNIST database data set.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] MNIST is composed of handwritten digits and includes 60,000 training examples and 10,000 test examples.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] As with TIMIT, its small size lets users test multiple configurations.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] A comprehensive list of results on this set is available.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-based image recognition has become "superhuman", producing more accurate results than human contestants.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This first occurred in 2011 in recognition of traffic signs, and in 2014, with recognition of human faces.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning-trained vehicles now interpret 360° camera views.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Another example is Facial Dysmorphology Novel Analysis (FDNA) used to analyze cases of human malformation connected to a large database of genetic syndromes.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Closely related to the progress that has been made in image recognition is the increasing application of deep learning techniques to various visual art tasks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Neural networks have been used for implementing language models since the early 2000s.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] LSTM helped to improve machine translation and language modeling.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Other key techniques in this field are negative sampling and word embedding.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Word embedding, such as *word2vec*, can be thought of as a representational layer in a deep learning architecture that transforms an atomic word into a positional representation of the word relative to other words in the dataset; the position is represented as a point in a vector space.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Using word embedding as an RNN input layer allows the network to parse sentences and phrases using an effective compositional vector grammar.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] A compositional vector grammar can be thought of as probabilistic context free grammar (PCFG) implemented by an RNN.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Recursive auto-encoders built atop word embeddings can assess sentence similarity and detect paraphrasing.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Recent developments generalize word embedding to sentence embedding.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate (GT) uses a large end-to-end long short-term memory (LSTM) network.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Google Neural Machine Translation (GNMT) uses an example-based machine translation method in which the system "learns from millions of examples".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] It translates "whole sentences at a time, rather than pieces".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate supports over one hundred languages.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The network encodes the "semantics of the sentence rather than simply memorizing phrase-to-phrase translations".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] GT uses English as an intermediate between most language pairs.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] A large percentage of candidate drugs fail to win regulatory approval.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] These failures are caused by insufficient efficacy (on-target effect), undesired interactions (off-target effects), or unanticipated toxic effects.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Research has explored use of deep learning to predict the biomolecular targets, off-targets, and toxic effects of environmental chemicals in nutrients, household products and drugs.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet is a deep learning system for structure-based rational drug design.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for disease targets such as the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 graph neural networks were used for the first time to predict various properties of molecules in a large toxicology data set.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2019, generative neural networks were used to produce molecules that were validated experimentally all the way into mice.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Recommendation systems have used deep learning to extract meaningful features for a latent factor model for content-based music and journal recommendations.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Multi-view deep learning has been applied for learning user preferences from multiple domains.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The model uses a hybrid collaborative and content-based approach and enhances recommendations in multiple tasks.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] An autoencoder ANN was used in bioinformatics, to predict gene ontology annotations and gene-function relationships.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In medical informatics, deep learning was used to predict sleep quality based on data from wearables and predictions of health complications from electronic health record data.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks have shown unparalleled performance in predicting protein structure, according to the sequence of the amino acids that make it up.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2020, AlphaFold, a deep-learning based system, achieved a level of accuracy significantly higher than all previous computational methods.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep neural networks can be used to estimate the entropy of a stochastic process through an arrangement called a Neural Joint Entropy Estimator (NJEE).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Such an estimation provides insights on the effects of input random variables on an independent random variable.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Practically, the DNN is trained as a classifier that maps an input vector or matrix X to an output probability distribution over the possible classes of random variable Y, given input X.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] For example, in image classification tasks, the NJEE maps a vector of pixels' color values to probabilities over possible image classes.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In practice, the probability distribution of Y is obtained by a Softmax layer with number of nodes that is equal to the alphabet size of Y.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] NJEE uses continuously differentiable activation functions, such that the conditions for the universal approximation theorem holds.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] It is shown that this method provides a strongly consistent estimator and outperforms other methods in cases of large alphabet sizes.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been shown to produce competitive results in medical applications such as cancer cell classification, lesion detection, organ segmentation and image enhancement.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Modern deep learning tools demonstrate the high accuracy of detecting various diseases and the helpfulness of their use by specialists to improve the diagnosis efficiency.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Finding the appropriate mobile audience for mobile advertising is always challenging, since many data points must be considered and analyzed before a target segment can be created and used in ad serving by any ad server.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been used to interpret large, many-dimensioned advertising datasets.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Many data points are collected during the request/serve/click internet advertising cycle.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This information can form the basis of machine learning to improve ad selection.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has been successfully applied to inverse problems such as denoising, super-resolution, inpainting, and film colorization.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] These applications include learning methods such as "Shrinkage Fields for Effective Image Restoration" which trains on an image dataset, and Deep Image Prior, which trains on the image that needs restoration.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is being applied to financial fraud detection, tax evasion detection, and anti-money laundering.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In November 2023, researchers at Google DeepMind and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory announced that they had developed an AI system known as GNoME.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This system has contributed to materials science by discovering over 2 million new materials within a relatively short timeframe.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] GNoME employs deep learning techniques to efficiently explore potential material structures, achieving a significant increase in the identification of stable inorganic crystal structures.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The system's predictions were validated through autonomous robotic experiments, demonstrating a noteworthy success rate of 71%.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The data of newly discovered materials is publicly available through the Materials Project database, offering researchers the opportunity to identify materials with desired properties for various applications.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This development has implications for the future of scientific discovery and the integration of AI in material science research, potentially expediting material innovation and reducing costs in product development.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The use of AI and deep learning suggests the possibility of minimizing or eliminating manual lab experiments and allowing scientists to focus more on the design and analysis of unique compounds.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The United States Department of Defense applied deep learning to train robots in new tasks through observation.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Physics-informed neural networks have been used to solve partial differential equations in both forward and inverse problems in a data driven manner.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] One example is the reconstructing fluid flow governed by the Navier-Stokes equations.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Using physics informed neural networks does not require the often expensive mesh generation that conventional CFD methods rely on.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] It is evident that geometric and physical constraints have a synergistic effect on neural PDE surrogates, thereby enhancing their efficacy in predicting stable and super long rollouts.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep backward stochastic differential equation method is a numerical method that combines deep learning with Backward stochastic differential equation (BSDE).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This method is particularly useful for solving high-dimensional problems in financial mathematics.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] By leveraging the powerful function approximation capabilities of deep neural networks, deep BSDE addresses the computational challenges faced by traditional numerical methods in high-dimensional settings.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Specifically, traditional methods like finite difference methods or Monte Carlo simulations often struggle with the curse of dimensionality, where computational cost increases exponentially with the number of dimensions.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep BSDE methods, however, employ deep neural networks to approximate solutions of high-dimensional partial differential equations (PDEs), effectively reducing the computational burden.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In addition, the integration of Physics-informed neural networks (PINNs) into the deep BSDE framework enhances its capability by embedding the underlying physical laws directly into the neural network architecture.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This ensures that the solutions not only fit the data but also adhere to the governing stochastic differential equations.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] PINNs leverage the power of deep learning while respecting the constraints imposed by the physical models, resulting in more accurate and reliable solutions for financial mathematics problems.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Image reconstruction is the reconstruction of the underlying images from the image-related measurements.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Several works showed the better and superior performance of the deep learning methods compared to analytical methods for various applications, e.g., spectral imaging and ultrasound imaging.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Traditional weather prediction systems solve a very complex system of partial differential equations.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] GraphCast is a deep learning based model, trained on a long history of weather data to predict how weather patterns change over time.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] It is able to predict weather conditions for up to 10 days globally, at a very detailed level, and in under a minute, with precision similar to state of the art systems.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] An epigenetic clock is a biochemical test that can be used to measure age.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Galkin et al. used deep neural networks to train an epigenetic aging clock of unprecedented accuracy using >6,000 blood samples.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The clock uses information from 1000 CpG sites and predicts people with certain conditions older than healthy controls: IBD, frontotemporal dementia, ovarian cancer, obesity.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The aging clock was planned to be released for public use in 2021 by an Insilico Medicine spinoff company Deep Longevity.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning is closely related to a class of theories of brain development (specifically, neocortical development) proposed by cognitive neuroscientists in the early 1990s.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] These developmental theories were instantiated in computational models, making them predecessors of deep learning systems.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] These developmental models share the property that various proposed learning dynamics in the brain (e.g., a wave of nerve growth factor) support the self-organization somewhat analogous to the neural networks utilized in deep learning models.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Like the neocortex, neural networks employ a hierarchy of layered filters in which each layer considers information from a prior layer (or the operating environment), and then passes its output (and possibly the original input), to other layers.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] This process yields a self-organizing stack of transducers, well-tuned to their operating environment.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] A 1995 description stated, "...the infant's brain seems to organize itself under the influence of waves of so-called trophic-factors ... different regions of the brain become connected sequentially, with one layer of tissue maturing before another and so on until the whole brain is mature".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] A variety of approaches have been used to investigate the plausibility of deep learning models from a neurobiological perspective.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] On the one hand, several variants of the backpropagation algorithm have been proposed in order to increase its processing realism.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Other researchers have argued that unsupervised forms of deep learning, such as those based on hierarchical generative models and deep belief networks, may be closer to biological reality.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In this respect, generative neural network models have been related to neurobiological evidence about sampling-based processing in the cerebral cortex.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Although a systematic comparison between the human brain organization and the neuronal encoding in deep networks has not yet been established, several analogies have been reported.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] For example, the computations performed by deep learning units could be similar to those of actual neurons and neural populations.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Similarly, the representations developed by deep learning models are similar to those measured in the primate visual system both at the single-unit and at the population levels.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Facebook's AI lab performs tasks such as automatically tagging uploaded pictures with the names of the people in them.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Google's DeepMind Technologies developed a system capable of learning how to play Atari video games using only pixels as data input.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2015 they demonstrated their AlphaGo system, which learned the game of Go well enough to beat a professional Go player.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Google Translate uses a neural network to translate between more than 100 languages.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2017, Covariant.ai was launched, which focuses on integrating deep learning into factories.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] First developed as TAMER, a new algorithm called Deep TAMER was later introduced in 2018 during a collaboration between U.S.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) and UT researchers.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep TAMER used deep learning to provide a robot with the ability to learn new tasks through observation.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Using Deep TAMER, a robot learned a task with a human trainer, watching video streams or observing a human perform a task in-person.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The robot later practiced the task with the help of some coaching from the trainer, who provided feedback such as "good job" and "bad job".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Deep learning has attracted both criticism and comment, in some cases from outside the field of computer science.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] A main criticism concerns the lack of theory surrounding some methods.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Learning in the most common deep architectures is implemented using well-understood gradient descent.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] However, the theory surrounding other algorithms, such as contrastive divergence is less clear.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] What is it approximating?) Deep learning methods are often looked at as a black box, with most confirmations done empirically, rather than theoretically.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] With the support of Innovation Diffusion Theory (IDT), a study analyzed the diffusion of deep learning in BRICS and OECD countries using data from Google Trends.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Some deep learning architectures display problematic behaviors, such as confidently classifying unrecognizable images as belonging to a familiar category of ordinary images (2014) and misclassifying minuscule perturbations of correctly classified images (2013).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Goertzel hypothesized that these behaviors are due to limitations in their internal representations and that these limitations would inhibit integration into heterogeneous multi-component artificial general intelligence (AGI) architectures.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] These issues may possibly be addressed by deep learning architectures that internally form states homologous to image-grammar decompositions of observed entities and events.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Learning a grammar (visual or linguistic) from training data would be equivalent to restricting the system to commonsense reasoning that operates on concepts in terms of grammatical production rules and is a basic goal of both human language acquisition and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] As deep learning moves from the lab into the world, research and experience show that artificial neural networks are vulnerable to hacks and deception.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] By identifying patterns that these systems use to function, attackers can modify inputs to ANNs in such a way that the ANN finds a match that human observers would not recognize.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] For example, an attacker can make subtle changes to an image such that the ANN finds a match even though the image looks to a human nothing like the search target.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Such manipulation is termed an "adversarial attack".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2016 researchers used one ANN to doctor images in trial and error fashion, identify another's focal points, and thereby generate images that deceived it.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The modified images looked no different to human eyes.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that printouts of doctored images then photographed successfully tricked an image classification system.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] One defense is reverse image search, in which a possible fake image is submitted to a site such as TinEye that can then find other instances of it.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] Another group showed that certain psychedelic spectacles could fool a facial recognition system into thinking ordinary people were celebrities, potentially allowing one person to impersonate another.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2017 researchers added stickers to stop signs and caused an ANN to misclassify them.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] ANNs can however be further trained to detect attempts at deception, potentially leading attackers and defenders into an arms race similar to the kind that already defines the malware defense industry.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] ANNs have been trained to defeat ANN-based anti-malware software by repeatedly attacking a defense with malware that was continually altered by a genetic algorithm until it tricked the anti-malware while retaining its ability to damage the target.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In 2016, another group demonstrated that certain sounds could make the Google Now voice command system open a particular web address, and hypothesized that this could "serve as a stepping stone for further attacks (e.g., opening a web page hosting drive-by malware)".
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] In "data poisoning", false data is continually smuggled into a machine learning system's training set to prevent it from achieving mastery.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The deep learning systems that are trained using supervised learning often rely on data that is created or annotated by humans, or both.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] It has been argued that not only low-paid clickwork (such as on Amazon Mechanical Turk) is regularly deployed for this purpose, but also implicit forms of human microwork that are often not recognized as such.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] The philosopher Rainer Mühlhoff distinguishes five types of "machinic capture" of human microwork to generate training data: (1) gamification (the embedding of annotation or computation tasks in the flow of a game), (2) "trapping and tracking" (e.g.
[src:onnx/deep-learning-p02] CAPTCHAs for image recognition or click-tracking on Google search results pages), (3) exploitation of social motivations (e.g. tagging faces on Facebook to obtain labeled facial images), (4) information mining (e.g. by leveraging quantified-self devices such as activity trackers) and (5) clickwork.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In the field of artificial intelligence, an **inference engine** is a software component of an intelligent system that applies logical rules to the knowledge base to deduce new information.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The first inference engines were components of expert systems.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The typical expert system consisted of a knowledge base and an inference engine.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The knowledge base stored facts about the world.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The inference engine applied logical rules to the knowledge base and deduced new knowledge.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] This process would iterate as each new fact in the knowledge base could trigger additional rules in the inference engine.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Inference engines work primarily in one of two modes either special rule or facts: forward chaining and backward chaining.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Forward chaining starts with the known facts and asserts new facts.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Backward chaining starts with goals, and works backward to determine what facts must be asserted so that the goals can be achieved.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Additionally, the concept of 'inference' has expanded to include the process through which trained neural networks generate predictions or decisions.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In this context, an 'inference engine' could refer to the specific part of the system, or even the hardware, that executes these operations.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] This type of inference plays a crucial role in various applications, including (but not limited to) image recognition, natural language processing, and autonomous vehicles.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The inference phase in these applications is typically characterized by a high volume of data inputs and real-time processing requirements.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The logic that an inference engine uses is typically represented as IF-THEN rules.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The general format of such rules is IF <logical expression> THEN <logical expression>.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Prior to the development of expert systems and inference engines, artificial intelligence researchers focused on more powerful theorem prover environments that offered much fuller implementations of first-order logic.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] For example, general statements that included universal quantification (for all X some statement is true) and existential quantification (there exists some X such that some statement is true).
[src:onnx/inference-engine] What researchers discovered is that the power of these theorem-proving environments was also their drawback.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Back in 1965, it was far too easy to create logical expressions that could take an indeterminate or even infinite time to terminate.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] For example, it is common in universal quantification to make statements over an infinite set such as the set of all natural numbers.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Such statements are perfectly reasonable and even required in mathematical proofs but when included in an automated theorem prover executing on a computer may cause the computer to fall into an infinite loop.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Focusing on IF-THEN statements (what logicians call *modus ponens*) still gave developers a very powerful general mechanism to represent logic, but one that could be used efficiently with computational resources.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] What is more, there is some psychological research that indicates humans also tend to favor IF-THEN representations when storing complex knowledge.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] A simple example of *modus ponens* often used in introductory logic books is "If you are human then you are mortal".
[src:onnx/inference-engine] A trivial example of how this rule would be used in an inference engine is as follows.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In *forward chaining*, the inference engine would find any facts in the knowledge base that matched Human(x) and for each fact it found would add the new information Mortal(x) to the knowledge base.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] So if it found an object called Socrates that was human it would deduce that Socrates was mortal.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In *backward chaining*, the system would be given a goal, e.g. answer the question is Socrates mortal?
[src:onnx/inference-engine] It would search through the knowledge base and determine if Socrates was human and, if so, would assert he is also mortal.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] However, in backward chaining a common technique was to integrate the inference engine with a user interface.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In that way, rather than simply being automated the system could now be interactive.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In this trivial example, if the system was given the goal to answer the question if Socrates was mortal and it didn't yet know if he was human, it would generate a window to ask the user the question "Is Socrates human?" and would then use that information accordingly.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] This innovation of integrating the inference engine with a user interface led to the second early advancement of expert systems: explanation capabilities.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The explicit representation of knowledge as rules rather than code made it possible to generate explanations to users: both explanations in real time and after the fact.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] At first these explanations were not much different than the standard debugging information that developers deal with when debugging any system.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] However, an active area of research was utilizing natural language technology to ask, understand, and generate questions and explanations using natural languages rather than computer formalisms.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] An inference engine cycles through three sequential steps: *match rules*, *select rules*, and *execute rules*.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The execution of the rules will often result in new facts or goals being added to the knowledge base, which will trigger the cycle to repeat.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] This cycle continues until no new rules can be matched.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In the first step, *match rules*, the inference engine finds all of the rules that are triggered by the current contents of the knowledge base.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In forward chaining, the engine looks for rules where the antecedent (left hand side) matches some fact in the knowledge base.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In backward chaining, the engine looks for antecedents that can satisfy one of the current goals.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In the second step, *select rules*, the inference engine prioritizes the various rules that were matched to determine the order to execute them.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] In the final step, *execute rules*, the engine executes each matched rule in the order determined in step two and then iterates back to step one again.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The cycle continues until no new rules are matched.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Early inference engines focused primarily on forward chaining.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] These systems were usually implemented in the Lisp programming language.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Lisp was a frequent platform for early AI research due to its strong capability to do symbolic manipulation.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Also, as an interpreted language it offered productive development environments appropriate to debugging complex programs.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] A necessary consequence of these benefits was that Lisp programs tended to be slower and less robust than compiled languages of the time such as C.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] A common approach in these early days was to take an expert system application and repackage the inference engine used for that system as a re-usable tool other researchers could use for the development of other expert systems.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] For example, MYCIN was an early expert system for medical diagnosis and EMYCIN was an inference engine extrapolated from MYCIN and made available for other researchers.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] As expert systems moved from research prototypes to deployed systems there was more focus on issues such as speed and robustness.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] One of the first and most popular forward chaining engines was OPS5, which used the Rete algorithm to optimize the efficiency of rule firing.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Another very popular technology that was developed was the Prolog logic programming language.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] Prolog focused primarily on backward chaining and also featured various commercial versions and optimizations for efficiency and robustness.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] As expert systems prompted significant interest from the business world, various companies, many of them started or guided by prominent AI researchers created productized versions of inference engines.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] For example, Intellicorp was initially guided by Edward Feigenbaum.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] These inference engine products were also often developed in Lisp at first.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] However, demands for more affordable and commercially viable platforms eventually made personal computer platforms very popular.
[src:onnx/inference-engine] ClipsRules and RefPerSys (inspired by CAIA and the work of Jacques Pitrat).
[src:onnx/inference-engine] The Frama-C static source code analyzer also uses some inference engine techniques.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Types of interoperability include **syntactic interoperability**, where two systems can communicate with each other, and cross-domain interoperability, where multiple organizations work together and exchange information.
[src:onnx/interoperability] If two or more systems use common data formats and communication protocols, then they are capable of communicating with each other, and they exhibit *syntactic interoperability*.
[src:onnx/interoperability] XML and SQL are examples of common data formats and protocols.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Low-level data formats also contribute to syntactic interoperability, ensuring that alphabetical characters are stored in the same ASCII or a Unicode format in all the communicating systems.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Beyond the ability of two or more computer systems to exchange information, semantic interoperability is the ability to automatically interpret the information exchanged meaningfully and accurately in order to produce useful results as defined by the end users of both systems.
[src:onnx/interoperability] To achieve semantic interoperability, both sides must refer to a common information exchange reference model.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The content of the information exchange requests are unambiguously defined: what is sent is the same as what is understood.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Cross-domain interoperability involves multiple social, organizational, political, legal entities working together for a common interest or information exchange.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability implies exchanges between a range of products, or similar products from several different vendors, or even between past and future revisions of the same product.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability may be developed *post-facto*, as a special measure between two products, while excluding the rest, by using open standards.
[src:onnx/interoperability] When a vendor is forced to adapt its system to a dominant system that is not based on open standards, it is compatibility, not interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Open standards rely on a broadly consultative and inclusive group, including representatives from vendors, academics and others holding a stake in the development that discusses and debates the technical and economic merits, demerits and feasibility of a proposed common protocol.
[src:onnx/interoperability] After the doubts and reservations of all members are addressed, the resulting common document is endorsed as a *common standard*.
[src:onnx/interoperability] This document may be subsequently released to the public, and henceforth becomes an *open standard*.
[src:onnx/interoperability] It is usually published and is available freely or at a nominal cost to any and all comers, with *no further encumbrances*.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The vendors' products compete on the quality of their implementation, user interface, ease of use, performance, price, and a host of other factors, while keeping the customer's data intact and transferable even if they choose to switch to another competing product for business reasons.
[src:onnx/interoperability] However, while "open" is a necessary condition for an interoperabilty standard, it is not a sufficient condition.
[src:onnx/interoperability] For example, the standard-setting processes for the Fortran, C, and C++ languages are open, with a broadly-inclusive consultative group.
[src:onnx/interoperability] But the resulting standards are not interoperability standards.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The data itself may be encumbered, e.g., by patents or pricing, leading to a dependence of all competing solutions on the original vendor, and possibly leading to a revenue stream from the competitors' customers back to the original vendor.
[src:onnx/interoperability] This revenue stream is the result of the original product's market dominance and not a result of any innate superiority.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Alternatively, it can be argued that even open processes are subject to the weight of past implementations and imperfect past designs and that the power of the dominant vendor to unilaterally correct or improve the system and impose the changes to all users facilitates innovation.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Lack of an open standard can also become problematic for the customers, as in the case of the original vendor's inability to fix a certain problem that is an artifact of technical limitations in the original product.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Speaking from an e-government perspective, interoperability refers to the collaboration ability of cross-border services for citizens, businesses and public administrations.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Exchanging data can be a challenge due to language barriers, different specifications of formats, varieties of categorizations and other hindrances.
[src:onnx/interoperability] If data is interpreted differently, collaboration is limited, takes longer and is inefficient.
[src:onnx/interoperability] For instance, if a citizen of country A wants to purchase land in country B, the person will be asked to submit the proper address data.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Address data in both countries includes full name details, street name and number, as well as a postal code.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The order of the address details might vary.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In the same language, it is not an obstacle to order the provided address data, but across language barriers, it becomes difficult.
[src:onnx/interoperability] If the language uses a different writing system it is almost impossible if no translation tools are available.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability is used by researchers in the context of urban flood risk management.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Cities and urban areas worldwide are expanding, which creates complex spaces with many interactions between the environment, infrastructure and people.
[src:onnx/interoperability] To address this complexity and manage water in urban areas appropriately, a system of systems approach to water and flood control is necessary.
[src:onnx/interoperability] At the strategic level, interoperability is an enabler for coalition building.
[src:onnx/interoperability] It facilitates meaningful contributions by coalition partners.
[src:onnx/interoperability] At this level, interoperability issues center on harmonizing world views, strategies, doctrines, and force structures.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability is an element of coalition willingness to work together over the long term to achieve and maintain shared interests against common threats.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability at the operational and tactical levels is where strategic interoperability and technological interoperability come together to help allies shape the environment, manage crises, and win wars.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The benefits of interoperability at the operational and tactical levels generally derive from the interchangeability of force elements and units.
[src:onnx/interoperability] *Technological interoperability* reflects the interfaces between organizations and systems.
[src:onnx/interoperability] It focuses on communications and computers but also involves the technical capabilities of systems and the resulting mission compatibility between the systems and data of coalition partners.
[src:onnx/interoperability] At the technological level, the benefits of interoperability come primarily from their impacts at the operational and tactical levels in terms of enhancing flexibility.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Because first responders need to be able to communicate during wide-scale emergencies, interoperability is an important issue for law enforcement, firefighting, emergency medical services, and other public health and safety departments.
[src:onnx/interoperability] It has been a major area of investment and research over the last 12 years.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Widely disparate and incompatible hardware impedes the exchange of information between agencies.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Agencies' information systems, such as computer-aided dispatch systems and records management systems, functioned largely in isolation, in so-called *information islands*.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Agencies tried to bridge this isolation with inefficient, stopgap methods while large agencies began implementing limited interoperable systems.
[src:onnx/interoperability] These approaches were inadequate and, in the US, the lack of interoperability in the public safety realm became evident during the 9/11 attacks on the Pentagon and World Trade Center structures.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Further evidence of a lack of interoperability surfaced when agencies tackled the aftermath of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In contrast to the overall national picture, some states, including Utah, have already made great strides forward.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The Utah Highway Patrol and other departments in Utah have created a statewide data sharing network.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The Commonwealth of Virginia is one of the leading states in the United States in improving interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The Interoperability Coordinator leverages a regional structure to better allocate grant funding around the Commonwealth so that all areas have an opportunity to improve communications interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The State of Washington seeks to enhance interoperability statewide.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Washington recognizes that collaborating on system design and development for wireless radio systems enables emergency responder agencies to efficiently provide additional services, increase interoperability, and reduce long-term costs.
[src:onnx/interoperability] This work saves the lives of emergency personnel and the citizens they serve.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The U.S. government is making an effort to overcome the nation's lack of public safety interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The Department of Homeland Security's Office for Interoperability and Compatibility (OIC) is pursuing the SAFECOM and CADIP and Project 25 programs, which are designed to help agencies as they integrate their CAD and other IT systems.
[src:onnx/interoperability] This project will partner the OIC with agencies in several locations, including Silicon Valley.
[src:onnx/interoperability] This program will use case studies to identify the best practices and challenges associated with linking CAD systems across jurisdictional boundaries.
[src:onnx/interoperability] These lessons will create the tools and resources public safety agencies can use to build interoperable CAD systems and communicate across local, state, and federal boundaries.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Governance entities can increase interoperability through their legislative and executive powers.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Conversely, government-mandated interoperability has been heavily criticized as leading to monopolies that become too big to fail.
[src:onnx/interoperability] For example, the United States Securities and Exchange Commission's implementation of 1975 amendments to the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 that were intended to ensure interoperability was blamed for driving all regional clearinghouses and depositories out of business in the United States.
[src:onnx/interoperability] As a result, the National Securities Clearing Corporation is the sole clearinghouse; the Depository Trust Company is the sole repository; and their parent, the Depository Trust & Clearing Corporation, has enormous market power over central counterparty clearing in the United States.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In contrast, the federal government of the United States did not attempt to mandate or regulate credit card interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] This allowed credit card networks to naturally develop interoperability (in the sense that almost every payment terminal can automatically accept almost every credit card), so that Visa Inc. was not left as the last credit card network standing.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Desktop interoperability is a subset of software interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In the early days, the focus of interoperability was to integrate web applications with other web applications.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Over time, open-system containers were developed to create a virtual desktop environment in which these applications could be registered and then communicate with each other using simple publish–subscribe patterns.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Rudimentary UI capabilities were also supported, allowing windows to be grouped with other windows.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Today, desktop interoperability has evolved into full-service platforms that include container support, basic exchange between web and web, but also native support for other application types and advanced window management.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The very latest interop platforms also include application services such as universal search, notifications, user permissions and preferences, 3rd party application connectors and language adapters for in-house applications.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Search interoperability refers to the ability of two or more information collections to be searched by a single query.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Specifically related to web-based search, the challenge of interoperability stems from the fact that designers of web resources typically have little or no need to concern themselves with exchanging information with other web resources.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Federated Search technology, which does not place format requirements on the data owner, has emerged as one solution to search interoperability challenges.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In addition, standards, such as Open Archives Initiative Protocol for Metadata Harvesting, Resource Description Framework, and SPARQL, have emerged that also help address the issue of search interoperability related to web resources.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Such standards also address broader topics of interoperability, such as allowing data mining.
[src:onnx/interoperability] With respect to software, the term *interoperability* is used to describe the capability of different programs to exchange data via a common set of exchange formats, to read and write the same file formats, and to use the same communication protocols.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The lack of interoperability can be a consequence of a lack of attention to standardization during the design of a program.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Indeed, interoperability is not taken for granted in the non-standards-based portion of the computing world.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Standards-developing organizations provide open public software specifications to facilitate interoperability; examples include the Oasis-Open organization and buildingSMART (formerly the International Alliance for Interoperability).
[src:onnx/interoperability] Another example of a neutral party is the RFC documents from the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:onnx/interoperability] The Open Service for Lifecycle Collaboration community is working on finding a common standard in order that software tools can share and exchange data e.g., bugs, tasks, requirements etc.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The final goal is to agree on an open standard for interoperability of open source application lifecycle management tools.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Java is an example of an interoperable programming language that allows for programs to be written once and run anywhere with a Java virtual machine.
[src:onnx/interoperability] A program in Java, so long as it does not use system-specific functionality, will maintain interoperability with all systems that have a Java virtual machine available.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Applications will maintain compatibility because, while the implementation is different, the underlying language interfaces are the same.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Product engineering Implements the common standard, or a sub-profile thereof, as defined by the industry and community partnerships with the specific intention of achieving interoperability with other software implementations, also following the same standard or sub-profile thereof.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Industry and community partnership Industry and community partnerships, either domestic or international, sponsor standard workgroups with the purpose of defining a common standard that may be used to allow software systems to intercommunicate for a defined purpose.
[src:onnx/interoperability] At times, an industry or community will sub-profile an existing standard produced by another organization to reduce options and thus make interoperability more achievable for implementations.
[src:onnx/interoperability] This technique has some of the same technical results as using a common vendor product to produce interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The common technology can come through third-party libraries or open-source developments.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Standard implementation Software interoperability requires a common agreement that is normally arrived at via an industrial, national or international standard.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Each of these has an important role in reducing variability in intercommunication software and enhancing a common understanding of the end goal to be achieved.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Language interoperability is the capability of two different programming languages to natively interact as part of the same system and operate on the same kind of data structures.
[src:onnx/interoperability] There are many ways programming languages are interoperable with one another.
[src:onnx/interoperability] HTML, CSS, and JavaScript are interoperable as they are used in tandem in webpages.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Some object oriented languages are interoperable thanks to their shared hosting virtual machine (e.g. .NET CLI compliant languages in the Common Language Runtime and JVM compliant languages in the Java Virtual Machine).
[src:onnx/interoperability] Unified interoperability is the property of a system that allows for the integration of real-time and non-real time communications, activities, data, and information services (i.e., unified) and the display and coordination of those services across systems and devices (i.e., interoperability).
[src:onnx/interoperability] Unified interoperability provides the capability to communicate and exchange processing across different applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability tends to be regarded as an issue for experts and its implications for daily living are sometimes underrated.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The European Union Microsoft competition case shows how interoperability concerns important questions of power relationships.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In 2004, the European Commission found that Microsoft had abused its market power by deliberately restricting interoperability between Windows Workgroup servers and non-Microsoft work group servers.
[src:onnx/interoperability] By doing so, Microsoft was able to protect its dominant market position for work group server operating systems, the heart of corporate IT networks.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Microsoft was ordered to disclose complete and accurate interface documentation, which could enable rival vendors to compete on an equal footing (*the interoperability remedy*).
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability has also surfaced in the software patent debate in the European Parliament (June–July 2005).
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability is often more of an organizational issue.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability can have a significant impact on the organizations concerned, raising issues of ownership (do people want to share their data? or are they dealing with information silos?), labor relations (are people prepared to undergo training?) and usability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In this context, a more apt definition is captured in the term *business process interoperability*.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Interoperability can have important economic consequences; for example, research has estimated the cost of inadequate interoperability in the US capital facilities industry to be $15.8 billion a year.
[src:onnx/interoperability] If competitors' products are not interoperable (due to causes such as patents, trade secrets or coordination failures), the result may well be monopoly or market failure.
[src:onnx/interoperability] For this reason, it may be prudent for user communities or governments to take steps to encourage interoperability in various situations.
[src:onnx/interoperability] At least 30 international bodies and countries have implemented eGovernment-based interoperability framework initiatives called e-GIF, while in the US, there is the NIEM initiative.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The need for *plug-and-play* interoperability – the ability to take a medical device out of its box and easily make it work with one's other devices – has attracted great attention from both healthcare providers and industry.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Increasingly, medical devices like incubators and imaging systems feature software that integrates at the point of care and with electronic systems, such as electronic medical records.
[src:onnx/interoperability] At the 2016 Regulatory Affairs Professionals Society (RAPS) meeting, experts in the field like Angela N.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Johnson with GE Healthcare and Jeff Shuren of the United States Food and Drug Administration, provided practical seminars on how companies developing new medical devices, and hospitals installing them, can work more effectively to align interoperable software systems.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Railways have greater or lesser interoperability depending on conforming to standards of gauge, couplings, brakes, signalling, loading gauge, and structure gauge to mention a few parameters.
[src:onnx/interoperability] For passenger rail service, different railway platform height and width clearance standards may also affect interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] North American freight and intercity passenger railroads are highly interoperable, but systems in Europe, Asia, Africa, Central and South America, and Australia are much less so.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The parameter most difficult to overcome (at reasonable cost) is incompatibility of gauge, though variable gauge axle systems can be used on rolling stock.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The condition achieved among communications-electronics systems or items of communications-electronics equipment when information or services can be exchanged directly and satisfactorily between them or their users.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The degree of interoperability should be defined when referring to specific cases.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Many organizations are dedicated to interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Some concentrate on eGovernment, eBusiness or data exchange in general.
[src:onnx/interoperability] Internationally, Network Centric Operations Industry Consortium facilitates global interoperability across borders, language and technical barriers.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In the built environment, the International Alliance for Interoperability started in 1994 and was renamed buildingSMART in 2005.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In Europe, the European Commission and its IDABC program issue the European Interoperability Framework.
[src:onnx/interoperability] IDABC was succeeded by the Interoperability Solutions for European Public Administrations (ISA) program.
[src:onnx/interoperability] They also initiated the Semantic Interoperability Centre Europe (SEMIC.EU).
[src:onnx/interoperability] A European Land Information Service (EULIS) was established in 2006, as a consortium of European National Land Registers.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The aim of the service is to establish a single portal through which customers are provided with access to information about individual properties, about land and property registration services, and about the associated legal environment.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The European Interoperability Framework (EIF) considered four kinds of interoperability: legal interoperability, organizational interoperability, semantic interoperability, and technical interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In the European Research Cluster on the Internet of Things (IERC) and IoT Semantic Interoperability Best Practices; four kinds of interoperability are distinguished: syntactical interoperability, technical interoperability, semantic interoperability, and organizational interoperability.
[src:onnx/interoperability] In the United States, the General Services Administration Component Organization and Registration Environment (CORE.GOV) initiative provided a collaboration environment for component development, sharing, registration, and reuse in the early 2000s.
[src:onnx/interoperability] A related initiative is the ongoing National Information Exchange Model (NIEM) work and component repository.
[src:onnx/interoperability] The National Institute of Standards and Technology serves as an agency for measurement standards.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:onnx/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
